<font color="#FF0000">TO COOK BARELA</font><br>
<tt>Sat Sep 13 17:06:55 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Cook,<br><br>
I appreciate your including Holy Scripture in this dialogue. It helps to make comparisons.<br><br>
Gideon was a judge. His understanding and forgiving those who were fearful and chose not to fight showed that he was a compassionate judge also.<br><br>
The fight against the Midianites was one sanctioned by God. Making a comparison with the war in Vietnam is ludicrous. <br><br>
Many posts up in this particular thread I addressed you about Lyndon Johnson, our Commander in Chief, abandoning our troops when he decided not to run for reelection. This was the turning point of the war. Many people began to have doubts. Many of our military leaders, who greatly underestimated the strength and determination of our enemy, continued to lie and deceive the citizens of America who looked to them for leadership. We were supposed to fight and die in a war that our leaders didn't believe in!<br><br>
God didn't abandon Gideon, while our politicians abandoned us.<br><br>
You are not the only person I have heard in my lifetime who maligned Conscientious Objectors. I knew several Quakers in Quang Ngai City. They had a clinic that made prosthetic devices for Vietnamese civilians. I was treated to the gruesome and macabre sight one day of a few dozen Vietnamese of all ages gathered in a courtyard - all missing at least one limb. This was only an infinitessimal cost of the war. And Quakers were there to pick up the pieces. To my knowledge they are still there.<br><br>
I think you are making real progress in your thoughts about the Winter Soldiers. Now you say that they were motivated by guilt. Congratulations. You have come a long way from the days when you stated their testimony was driven by communist propaganda.<br><br>
Yes! The Winter Soldiers were in Vietnam for all the wrong reasons. So was I. But, the funny thing was that the US Government wasn't required to give me a *REASON* as to why it saw fit to send me to Vietnam. It was fight  for something I had no belief in, or go to jail. I chose the former because the people from whom I sought guidance said that I should. When I came home, many acted like I had never been gone! They turned their backs on me. And I am willing to bet that those same people -who were the ones who should have given me a homecoming - are now caught up in blaming the war protestors for our mistreatment! They have a guilt trip of their own - as well they should. <br><br>
Guilt, as far as the Winter Soldiers is concerned, is part of the healing process, so is remorse. These come shortly after denial.<br>

<p><code>-- wingman@greene.xtn.net  (Tom Dier) </code><p>


